  "prompt": "Why can't radio waves transmit through water?",
  "response": "Radio waves *can* transmit through water, but the degree to which they can and how far they can travel depends heavily on their **frequency** and the **conductivity** of the water.  It's more accurate to say they are **attenuated** (weakened) by water, rather than completely blocked.\n\nHere's the breakdown:\n\n*   **Attenuation and Frequency:**\n    *   **Low-frequency radio waves:** Penetrate water much better than high-frequency waves. This is because water molecules are more easily agitated by high-frequency electromagnetic fields, absorbing their energy and converting it to heat.\n    *   **High-frequency radio waves:** Are rapidly absorbed by water. Their energy is used to vibrate the water molecules, leading to significant signal loss over short distances.\n\n*   **Conductivity of Water:**\n    *   **Pure water:** Would be a relatively poor conductor of electricity, and radio waves would theoretically travel further.\n    *   **Saltwater:** Is a good conductor due to the dissolved salts (ions). These ions interact with the electromagnetic fields of radio waves, causing significant absorption and scattering of the signal. Fresh water with minerals has similar, although lesser effects.\n\n**Think of it like shining a light through murky water:**\n\n*   **Low-frequency waves (like red light):** Can penetrate further, but still get dimmer over distance.\n*   **High-frequency waves (like blue light):** Get absorbed very quickly, so you can't see them very far.\n\n**Specific Examples and Uses:**\n\n*   **Very Low Frequency (VLF) radio waves (3-30 kHz):** Used for communicating with submarines. They can penetrate seawater to a depth of a few meters to tens of meters. The data transfer rate is very slow due to the low frequency.\n*   **Extremely Low Frequency (ELF) radio waves (3-300 Hz):** Can penetrate seawater to much greater depths (hundreds of meters), but the data transfer rate is extremely slow (practically non-existent for real-time communication).\n*   **Higher Frequency radio waves (e.g., FM radio):** Are essentially useless for underwater communication.\n\n**In summary:**\n\nRadio waves *can* transmit through water, but the extent depends strongly on their frequency and the water's conductivity. Lower frequencies penetrate better because they are less easily absorbed by water molecules and ions. Saltwater absorbs radio waves more readily than freshwater. This is why underwater communication relies primarily on very low frequencies.\n",
